abstract: Closing arguments Monday in President Donald Trump's impeachment trial were directed more toward history than to sway the outcome, one final chance to influence public opinion and set the record ahead of his expected acquittal in the Republican-led Senate.

abstract: Those moderate senators, some of whom are up for re-election in November, have left the door open.
snippet: Those moderate senators, some of whom are up for re-election in November, have left the door open.
lead_paragraph: The few remaining senators who have stayed mum on whether they will vote to acquit President Trump rebuffed more attempts to gain insight into their thinking on Monday morning.
headline_main: Undecided senators hold their cards close to their chest.

abstract: They seemed to be eying the public, and history, though, as much as the hearing room.
snippet: They seemed to be eying the public, and history, though, as much as the hearing room.
lead_paragraph: The House Democratic impeachment managers began one final overview of their case on Monday, making a raw and likely vain appeal to Republican senators to reconsider their intended acquittal of President Trump. They seemed to be eying the public, and history, though, as much as the hearing room.

abstract: U.S. President Donald Trump and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau discussed their countries' efforts to monitor, contain, and mitigate the rapidly spreading new coronavirus in a phone call on Friday, the White House said.
snippet: U.S. President Donald Trump and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau discussed their countries' efforts to monitor, contain, and mitigate the rapidly spreading new coronavirus in a phone call on Friday, the White House said.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. President Donald Trump and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau discussed their countries' efforts to monitor, contain, and mitigate the rapidly spreading new coronavirus in a phone call on Friday, the White House said.
headline_main: Trump and Trudeau Discussed Coronavirus in Friday Phone Call
headline_print_headline: Trump and Trudeau Discussed Coronavirus in Friday Phone Call

abstract: U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo emphasized Washington's support for Ukraine on a visit to Kiev on Friday, as both countries sought to smooth over relations buffeted by the impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
snippet: U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo emphasized Washington's support for Ukraine on a visit to Kiev on Friday, as both countries sought to smooth over relations buffeted by the impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
lead_paragraph: KIEV — U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo emphasized Washington's support for Ukraine on a visit to Kiev on Friday, as both countries sought to smooth over relations buffeted by the impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
headline_main: Pompeo Pledges Support for Ukraine as Impeachment Trial Rumbles
headline_print_headline: Pompeo Pledges Support for Ukraine as Impeachment Trial Rumbles

abstract: When Palestinian leaders learned that the release of U.S. President Donald Trump's Middle East plan was imminent, they swiftly announced a "day of rage" - a gritty, oft-used call for resistance against Israel.
snippet: When Palestinian leaders learned that the release of U.S. President Donald Trump's Middle East plan was imminent, they swiftly announced a "day of rage" - a gritty, oft-used call for resistance against Israel.
lead_paragraph: JERUSALEM — When Palestinian leaders learned that the release of U.S. President Donald Trump's Middle East plan was imminent, they swiftly announced a "day of rage" - a gritty, oft-used call for resistance against Israel.
headline_main: Palestinians Face Uphill Battle Against Trump's Middle East Plan
headline_print_headline: Palestinians Face Uphill Battle Against Trump's Middle East Plan

abstract: The Trump administration on Thursday said it will allow Russian, Chinese and European companies to continue their work at Iranian nuclear sites, arguing that their presence makes it harder for Tehran to develop nuclear weapons.
snippet: The Trump administration on Thursday said it will allow Russian, Chinese and European companies to continue their work at Iranian nuclear sites, arguing that their presence makes it harder for Tehran to develop nuclear weapons.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON/PARIS — The Trump administration on Thursday said it will allow Russian, Chinese and European companies to continue their work at Iranian nuclear sites, arguing that their presence makes it harder for Tehran to develop nuclear weapons.
headline_main: U.S. Renews Waivers on Iran Nuclear Work, but Sanctions Top Iran Nuclear Official
headline_print_headline: U.S. Renews Waivers on Iran Nuclear Work, but Sanctions Top Iran Nuclear Official
